Restituere in 6 general sense denotes any un- doing of 6 wrong, any replacement of 6 person or 1116 right in his or its original condition, whether by the voluntary act of the wrongdoer, or after action brought, and then either at the invi- tation of the judge (in virtue of the clause, ni restituat, 4 ᾧ 47), or in execution of 6 judicial sentence. But in the phrase we 616 examining it denotes the act, not of 6 private party, but of a judicial authority. In integrum restitutio is the restitution by the praetor of a person or his right to his or its original uninjured con- dition, in cases when no remedy is to be obtained either from the rigorous mles of the civil law or jus strictum (e. g. by civilis actio), or even from equity as administered by the ordinary judges in the ordinary forms (6. g. by exceptio or bonae fidei actio).
